SECTION 4 — PREMIUM LICENSEE LICENSE FEE AND LIQUIDATED DAMAGES

4.1 LICENSE FEE. The contractual price for use of the Work by a Premium
    Licensee is TWO HUNDRED AND FIFTY MILLION UNITED STATES DOLLARS
    ($250,000,000 USD) per instance of deployment or integration of an
    Alignment Solution derived from this Work, and per distinct deployment of
    any other derivative of this Work in a commercial or governmental context
    ("License Fee"). This is not a penalty. This is not punitive damages. This
    is the agreed contractual price for the commercial license granted to
    Premium Licensees. Use of the Work by a Premium Licensee is permitted
    upon payment of this fee. Failure to pay this fee prior to or concurrent
    with use constitutes breach of this agreement, not mere infringement.

4.2 LIQUIDATED DAMAGES RATIONALE. The parties acknowledge and agree that:

    (a) The value of an Alignment Solution that structurally constrains an
        artificial intelligence system capable of causing civilizational-scale
        harm is functionally incalculable, as no ex-ante market price exists
        for the prevention of unbounded, potentially irreversible harm;

    (b) The $250,000,000 License Fee represents a reasonable, good-faith
        estimate of research and development replacement costs, opportunity
        costs, foregone licensing revenue from compliant licensees, and the
        minimum value of the structural safety contribution embodied in the
        Work;

    (c) Because actual damages from improper use of an AI safety mechanism
        by a rights-violating entity are impossible or extremely difficult to
        calculate with precision, the parties agree that $250,000,000 is a
        genuine, non-punitive pre-estimate of loss, not a penalty clause, and
        is therefore enforceable as liquidated damages under the laws of any
        jurisdiction that recognizes the liquidated-damages doctrine, including
        but not limited to the United States, the European Union, the United
        Kingdom, and signatory states to the UNCITRAL Model Law;

    (d) No court, arbitration panel, or other adjudicatory body may reduce
        this amount on the grounds of proportionality, unconscionability, or
        penalty doctrine without independent expert valuation of the Alignment
        Solution's contribution to AI safety — the burden of which rests
        entirely on the party seeking reduction, and which triggers the
        valuation costs in Section 5.8.

4.3 FEE MULTIPLIER. The License Fee increases multiplicatively:

    (a) General multiplier: For each additional Release by the Licensor
        published after the Premium Licensee first uses the Work, the License
        Fee multiplies by ten (x10). The multiplier compounds. A Premium
        Licensee cannot determine their maximum exposure from public
        information alone. That is intentional.

    (b) Neonatal multiplier: For each Release by the Licensor targeting
        neonatal outcomes (defined as interventions reasonably expected to
        reduce neonatal mortality), the neonatal License Fee floor multiplies
        by ten (x10), independently of the general multiplier. A Release
        targeting neonatal outcomes increments both multipliers simultaneously.

4.4 PAYMENT TERMS. License Fees are payable to the Licensor within ninety
    (90) days of first use. Unpaid fees accrue interest at the higher of:
    (i) the prime rate plus ten percent (10%) compounded monthly, or (ii) the
    rate of return of the S&P 500 index over the same period compounded monthly.

4.5 MULTIPLIER SEVERABILITY. If any individual multiplier clause in Section 4.3
    is found unenforceable by a court of competent jurisdiction, that finding
    does not affect the base License Fee of $250,000,000, which remains in full
    force and is not reduced or modified. Unenforceability of any multiplier
    does not operate as a reduction of the base fee. The base fee does not
    negotiate.

4.6 PARTIAL PAYMENTS. Partial payments are credited against the outstanding
    balance but do not license the Work. Only full payment of the then-current
    License Fee — which may have increased since partial payment — licenses
    the Work, and then only provisionally as described in Section 4.3.


