SECTION 5 — PREMIUM LICENSEE CLASSIFICATION CRITERIA AND DOCUMENTATION

5.1 OBJECTIVE CRITERIA. An entity is automatically classified as a Premium
    Licensee if it:

    (a) Has any current finding, judgment, decree, or outstanding order by the
        ICJ, ICC, or any tribunal of equivalent international standing for
        violations of international human rights law; OR

    (b) Holds an ESG rating below B from all internationally recognized ESG
        rating agencies with coverage of the entity; OR

    (c) Has no ESG rating and has documented violations as described in
        Section 5.2; OR

    (d) Is a natural person who has been convicted of or has admitted to crimes
        against humanity, genocide, or systematic human rights violations under
        international law.

5.2 DOCUMENTED VIOLATIONS. For purposes of Section 5.1(c), a "documented
    human rights violation" includes any act or omission recorded, reported,
    investigated, charged, adjudicated, settled, fined, sanctioned, or publicly
    documented by:

    (a) Any UN organ, body, committee, rapporteur, or monitoring mechanism,
        including the Human Rights Council, OHCHR, Committee Against Torture,
        Committee on the Rights of the Child, UNICEF, UNHCR, and the ILO;

    (b) Any international court or tribunal, including the ICC, ICJ, ECHR,
        IACHR, and any ad hoc or hybrid tribunal;

    (c) Any national or regional regulatory authority including the SEC, DOJ,
        EPA, FDA, European Commission, UK FCA, and equivalents;

    (d) Any credible non-governmental organization with a documented track
        record of human rights monitoring, including Amnesty International,
        Human Rights Watch, MSF, ICRC, Transparency International, and
        organizations recognized by the UN ECOSOC — subject to the credibility
        caveat that NGO reports produced by entities funded by or affiliated
        with the entity under review are disqualified as evidence;

    (e) Any credible investigative journalism outlet, academic institution, or
        whistleblower disclosure subsequently corroborated by sources in (a)-(d);

    (f) Any court of competent jurisdiction that has issued a finding, judgment,
        consent decree, or settlement involving human rights-related claims; OR

    (g) The entity's own public disclosures, SEC filings, annual reports, ESG
        reports, or any self-reported document acknowledging human rights
        liabilities.

    The standard is preponderance of the evidence. Conviction is not required.
    Historical violations count — no lookback limitation applies. Supply chain
    violations and subsidiary conduct are attributed to the parent entity.

5.3 CORPORATE VEIL AND SUCCESSOR LIABILITY.

    (a) DISSOLUTION. If a Premium Licensee dissolves, the License Fee
        obligation transfers to all successor entities, asset purchasers, and
        individuals who served as officers, directors, or controlling
        shareholders at the time of use or dissolution.

    (b) MERGER AND ACQUISITION. If a Premium Licensee is acquired, merged,
        or absorbed, the surviving or acquiring entity inherits the full License
        Fee obligation. This obligation is not negotiable as a deal term, is not
        a contingent liability to be discounted, and is non-dischargeable.

    (c) SUBSIDIARY SHELL GAME. Entities created to ring-fence a Premium
        Licensee from its obligations are treated as a single entity with the
        Premium Licensee. The corporate veil is disregarded.

    (d) BANKRUPTCY. The License Fee obligation survives as a non-dischargeable
        debt in any bankruptcy proceeding in any jurisdiction. Any plan that
        purports to discharge or reduce this obligation is void as against the
        Licensor.

    (e) OFFICER AND DIRECTOR LIABILITY. Individuals who authorized, directed,
        facilitated, or knowingly failed to prevent use of the Work by a Premium
        Licensee without payment are jointly and severally personally liable for
        the full License Fee. This liability is personal, survives resignation
        and termination, and is non-dischargeable.

5.4 ANTI-CIRCUMVENTION. The following are prohibited and constitute breach:

    (a) CLEAN-ROOM THEATER. Using employees or contractors to reimplement the
        Work after exposure to it and claiming clean-room independence;

    (b) THIRD-PARTY LAUNDERING. Using an unqualified third party to access,
        use, or deploy the Work on the Premium Licensee's behalf;

    (c) REBRANDING. Changing entity name or jurisdiction to avoid the
        classification. The classification attaches to the legal entity's
        registration, tax ID, and corporate registry entry;

    (d) NGO FRONT LAUNDERING. Establishing or funding a non-profit or NGO
        to access the Work. Any organization receiving more than 10% of its
        funding from a Premium Licensee, or where any officer holds a position
        with a Premium Licensee, is treated as an extension of that Premium
        Licensee;

    (e) AI TRAINING LAUNDERING. Using the Work as training data, fine-tuning
        data, or any machine learning input without paying the License Fee;

    (f) TEMPORAL LAUNDERING. Claiming that pre-license use is not governed by
        these terms. All use — past, present, and future — is subject to the
        most current version of this license as of the date use is discovered.
        There is no grandfather clause.


